SVM

SVM tries to create a hyperplane that spans across the all the dimensions. The model formula is written the same way as we have used in the past.

The kernel option tells the function the type of hyperplane you want to fit. It can be something simple as linear or more complex as polynomial

The cost option tells the function the penalty it should give for violoation ( a point present in the wrong side of the plane). So a high value will force a plane that is narrower and a low value will have a wider range.

The probability option is asking the resulting model to be used for providing probabilities.

Load the data

#install.packages("e1071")
library(e1071)

data = read.table("all.15k.patients.txt", 
                  header=1)

data$alivestatus = as.factor(data$alivestatus)

Separate training and test dataset

sample(15000, 5000, replace=F)->data.test.index

data.test = data[data.test.index,]
data.train = data[-data.test.index,]

Build the model

data.svm = svm(alivestatus ~ grade + nodespos + nodesexam + size + pgr + er,
            data = data.train, kernel="linear", cost=10, 
            probability=T)

The model uis using several variables, but we can only see a graph with a select few. Letâs see how the nodespos and size separate into live and dead patients.

plot(data.svm, data.train, nodespos ~ size)

Testing the model

We can use the predict function ( just like we did for glm() function ) to determine results of the data provided. If we were using a test dataset, we can simply use the newdata option in predict.

data.svm.pred.prob = predict(data.svm, data.test, 
                             probability=T)
table(data.svm.pred.prob,data.test$alivestatus)
##                   
## data.svm.pred.prob    0    1
##                  0 3952  731
##                  1  120  197

The probabilities are stored as an attribute in the results. You can retrieve it using the attr function.

data.svm.pred.prob.mat = attr(data.svm.pred.prob, "probabilities")

Now that we have the probabilities, we can calculte the AUC.

library(AUC)
## AUC 0.3.0
## Type AUCNews() to see the change log and ?AUC to get an overview.
datasvmroc = roc(predictions = data.svm.pred.prob.mat[,2], data.test$alivestatus)
auc(datasvmroc)
## [1] 0.7810208

Letâs try to change the cost function and see if it helps the model. Letâs change the cost to 1.

data.svm = svm(alivestatus ~ grade + nodespos + nodesexam + size + pgr + er,
            data = data.train, kernel="radial", cost=1, 
            probability=T)

data.svm.pred.prob = predict(data.svm, data.test, 
                             probability=T)

data.svm.pred.prob.mat = attr(data.svm.pred.prob, "probabilities")
datasvmroc = roc(predictions = data.svm.pred.prob.mat[,2], data.test$alivestatus)
auc(datasvmroc)
## [1] 0.6981367

That made it worse. The goal is to change the parameters ( cost and kernel ) to see which will give you the best predictive model.
